segments.text: Was that a jeweler downtown or was it on, where was he?
This was in Bryan.
In Bryan, in Bryan.
How often did you and your buddies go to Bryan when you were a student?
Oh, not too often, but some, yes.
And how did you get there?
They had a trolley.
Went by trolley.
Do you remember what it cost?
I think it cost a nickel.
It didn't cost much because if it cost more than a nickel, I don't think I'd have made it.
And it ran every hour or so?
Yeah, it ran, yeah.
And what was there in downtown Bryan for an Aggie that was interesting?
Movies.
Movies and going to a restaurant.
Getting whatever you can buy.
Do you remember seeing any movies down there that made an impression on you?
Were there some special?
Oh, I don't remember.
I don't remember.
Let's see.
Were there still some silent movies?
Oh, sure, because sound didn't come in.
The first sound came in in 1927.
That's what I...
And there was silent movies up to that time.
And the first movie with sound, it was Al Jolson.
And then after that, of course, you had sound.
Do you remember seeing that?
Did you see that one?
I saw that one, yes.
What did you think of it?
Well, I thought it was great.
You sit there, and all of a sudden, you hear voices.
from a movie.
It was really something.
To me, it was a great, great development.
How many students had a radio then?
Oh, I think most of them.
Really?
Oh, yeah.
Radio was prevalent.
And you listened to WTAW and what other stations?
I listened to whatever station they went to.
There was one station I used to listen to, and that was
What's his name?
Godfrey?
Godfrey?
Godfrey played the Hawaiian music all the time.
And at that time it was microwave.
And he was in Hawaii.
Relay the music and it'll fade in and fade out.
Fade in and fade out.
Wasn't clear.
Your freshman year, did you go home Thanksgiving?
I went home Christmas.
Christmas.
How did you get home?
Well, most of the time, I thought my way home.
Describe Aggie hitchhiking.
What was it like?
Well, there'd be more than one trying to hitchhike, and we separated about 200 yards.
Everybody had a chance.
Did you wear a uniform?
Oh, absolutely, that's the only way that people will stop.
They knew Aggies.
They knew Aggies with uniforms on, you know.

They were the same people driving up and down the highways in the trucks and mostly, and I've ridden many times in a truck that was being delivered someplace and that they'll take me halfway or the quarter way or to Houston and then I'd go on the road and try to get all the way into Bowman.
Did you ever have any bad Aggie hitchhiking experience?
No, never did.
This is number 204 of the interviews.
I have yet to hear a single bad hitchhiking experience.
Everybody says, sometimes did the guy drive a little too fast or maybe drink a little too much?
I never had any experience.
Of course, I didn't make as many trips as some of them made.
Because I stayed here and I worked.
What did you tell your parents and your friends that first Christmas about being an Aggie?
What did you tell them?
I couldn't tell my mother much.
She wanted to know why my rear end was so bloody and everything else.
And that was the whole talk the whole time I was there.
She just felt like I was in the wrong place.
And she was the one who really wanted me to go to college.
And she just would save a dollar here, 50 cents or whatever it is, and try to send it to me whenever she possibly could.
She was a great mother.
About how much did it cost a full year then?
Do you have any idea to go to A&M?
I think that less than $200.
And about how much did you earn and how much did your family give you?
Oh, my family.
My mother would give me maybe $4 or $5 a month.
That's just shit saved.
We were poor.
We were very poor.
And the grocery store was just making enough to
to keep us alive, you might say.
And there was no way that my family could have sent me to college.
No way.
I can identify with some of this because nobody in either of my parents' families had ever finished high school before me.
My parents didn't.
But they always said, you're going to go to college.
You're going to go to college.
My mother supported me too.
My daddy, he was a good man, but he was striving, working so hard to keep the family together and everything.
He felt like that we ought to work in the store and help them.
Did your brothers and sisters go to college?
My older brother didn't.
My other brothers did.
And I helped one of them get a degree out of Tulane.
He was a wonderful doctor.
Oh, great.
And he was the first of the brothers to die.
Did you ever think about leaving A&M and going somewhere else?
No, I should say not.
When I came to A&M and I got that $50
I would have done anything for A&M.
Anything, anything.
At Christmas, then, you go home and you're coming back.
Did the hazing slow down the second semester for freshmen?
Somewhat, because if I remember, one of the freshmen had a hurt, his spine was damaged.
And I really led a contingent because I did everything I possibly could to stop that hazing.
When you finished your freshman year, what did you do that summer after your freshman year?
I went to Beaumont and I worked in the oil refinery, hauling coke.
They'd have this coke and they liked to haul it and put it on gondolas.
I'd get out just black, and they'd pay you so much an hour.
I worked in the oil fields.
After the second boom, it spilt up.
I'd carry buckets.
But fresh water buckets in each hand and carry them to people on the rig on the derrick floor.
And they paid me 50 cents.
50 cents?
50 cents a day.
Oh, a day.
For the afternoon.
Oh, I thought you were going to say an hour.
No, no, they paid me 50 cents.
Now, Beaumont was a boontown then, wasn't it?
Well, they had a boom town in 1901.
Yes.
When the film town came in on the Superdome structure.
But on the flake, that was 1925.
That's what I thought.
I was still in high school.
So there was a second boom.
A second boom.
And you came back then as a sophomore.
How much better was it to be an Aggie sophomore than it was to be an Aggie freshman?
Well, a hell of a lot better.

a lot better you you just don't realize some of the things that the hazing that took place there were dropouts there was some that went home i couldn't take it but i took it regardless of what it was because i wanted this i wanted the education i was determined i was going to be a geoscientist and i was going to do it
Now did you think that you were going to be a scholar, a geoscience scholar, or that you were going to go into the business world?
No, I wanted to get my degree.
I got my bachelor's degree.

Then I went back and got my master's degree because Dr. Lonsdale, who was head of the science department and all, had made arrangements with the United States Geological Survey to do some work in the Winter Garden area, which was near the valley.
And so he asked me to be his assistant.
Oh, good.
And so they paid me a few dollars to work and write up the papers and things of that kind.
And I got my master's degree by working the geology out of Scotia County.
As a sophomore, did you have jobs the same way as you had as a freshman?
Oh, yes, I worked the same way.
I worked the same way I did through my junior year, and then during my junior year, the class elected me as editor of the Longhorn.
I always wondered why it was called a Longhorn, and I recommended that it be changed to the Aggieland, and it finally was.
And the word Longhorn was two words, wasn't it?
No, no.
Oh, originally it was two.
Longhorn.
Originally it was two words.
I don't remember that.
Well, back in the 1890s.
Where were the offices for the Longhorn?
In Milner.
In Milner Hall?
Milner.
My junior year, I was in Milner.
I think I was in Milner both years, junior and senior.
Now, had you done any...
work like that before in high school?
No, no.
It just came natural to me.
My business manager was Quack Porter.
Quack Porter.
Yeah, they called him Quack.
Where was he from?
Do you remember?
I don't, but I thought about him the other day and I said, I'm gonna get in touch with Quack.
I could find out.
Terrell, Texas?
I know where that is, east of Dallas.
I think it's Terrell.
What was your nickname?
Mike.
No other than Mike.
It's Mike.
Michelle is my name.
Yes, sir, I know.
Were you Mike in high school or were you Michelle in high school?
Both.
Both?
The teachers called me Michelle.
And the students, some called me Michelle.
The girls called me Michelle, but the boys called me Mike.
They didn't like the name Michelle.
Back to the Longhorn, about how many other students worked with you on the Longhorn staff?
Oh, I had, oh, maybe 25.

and uh longhorn when when you were elected editor and business manager you had to raise the money and how did you raise it quack and i bought a car for 75 dollars an old star the name of a star didn't have a top oh dilapidated car and so we took that we toured toured the state
Raising money?
We may have raised money.
We had to, otherwise we couldn't get the book.
The school didn't give us a dime, not one dime.
How much did you all raise?
We raised enough to publish it, and I think it was pretty close to $10,000, if I'm not mistaken.
Wow, that's a lot of money.
Our biggest contributor was Zachary.
H.B.
Zachary?
The greatest contributor.
There.
That's his picture, but it's on the John.
That's Mr. Zachary's picture.
Yeah.
We walked in and he said, what are you going to do?
I said, well, you know about this, Mr. Zachary.
You've been to A&M.
You know what the yearbook is.
School doesn't give us a dime.
We've got to raise the money ourselves.
And we did everything.
We went from one place to the other, and we solicited, and we met people that we would have never met before.
And sometimes we were hungry, and we didn't spend money to really eat.
I remember one time we were coming back from San Antonio, we passed some watermelon
I said, quack, let's go in there and get the watermelon.
He said, oh, hell no, we may be shot.
I said, I'm hungry.
They said the watermelon was close to the road.
I said, well, I'm going in there and get the watermelon.
He said, no, you better watch out.
So anyway, I jumped over the fence and got a watermelon.
We bursted it open, and that was our meal for the day, I think.
Who else was truly helpful other than Mr. Zachary?
Were there some others?
Oh yeah, we got, I don't remember names, but Dallas, we had a lot of help in Dallas.
Amarillo, Beaumont,
Corpus Christi.
And that area helped us a lot, and the valley.
Where did you get the idea for that marvelous artwork that you put in that?
Do you know?
I'm glad you brought it up because that's the greatest piece of artwork that was ever in any annual.
Did you know that it won All-America Prize?
It was considered the best annual of any annual for that year in the whole country.
I thought that looking into the future, and I got this, Mr. Dr. Geiss.
He was associated with the architecture department.
G-E-I-S-S?
G-E-I-S. S. I think that's the spelling.
And I said, I said, now look, Dr. Geiss, I want, this is the idea I have.
I said, someday they're going to be planes flying all over the place.
I said, we want to build high-rise buildings, connect them.
And I said, we also want to build a landing place in the middle of the ocean so that planes can leave the United States, land, get gasoline, and move on.
Have you seen that book?
Mm-hmm.
Now, who did the art?
He did.
Oh, Professor Geist did.
Professor Geist, he had a...
He had two helpers, I can't remember their name.
Students.
That's beautiful work.
Oh, yes.
There'd be nothing like it.
Nothing.
Did he?
Even to this day, from 1930 to this day, no annual ever came close.
Now, did he get any pay for that, or did he donate all of it?
No, no, this was all volunteer.
The money that we got, we paid for expenses.
We had to have this, we had to have that, we had to have typewriters.
The school didn't give us anything.
Where was it printed?
It was printed in Jefferson City, Missouri.
Really?
Yes.
Because, see, I was chancellor of the University of Missouri after I left here and came back four years ago.
That's why I'll have to check on the company.
Jefferson City, Missouri.
My, my, my.
Because the Aggieland today is being printed by a company up in North Missouri.
Yeah.
They're very, very big in that.
It might have been the same company.
Oh, that's what I'm going to check.
Do you remember how many copies you all printed?
Enough for all the student body.
So it would have been 2,000 plus.
Whatever it was.
I think my class was around 2,100. Who did the photography?

all of us so different people yes i had a camera a quack had a camera and i designated some of them to do go go get pictures here go get pictures of the military go get pictures of the athletic program things like that were there any faculty advisors none none it's remarkable
that here was something so important for the university at that time, the college.
And there was no help of any kind from the faculty or from the officers of the institution.
And I'm trying to think who was there.
Chairman of the Board of Regents.
Wait a minute, look at me.
I'm sure I don't know that one.
Anyway, I went to him.
And I told him, I said, how in the world can this college want a yearbook?
They needed a yearbook, and there's no help.
I said, maybe next year you're not going to get somebody as enterprising as Hal Booney and Porter.
Maybe they won't be able to go get the money.
What are you going to do?
Now when did y'all make that fundraising trip?
Was it during the summer?
During the summer, between the junior and senior years.
You were elected while you were a junior.
Now had you worked on the yearbook as a junior?
No, I did a little photography and then I'd go into the office and I think the editor of the one before that was Puryear.
Was it Puryear or do you know?
Now did somebody recommend you?
Or did you just kind of say, hey, I'd like to do this?
It was a surprise to me.
Oh, really?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
The president of the class came to me and told me that I was elected to be editor, and Quack Porter was elected to be business manager.
And I said, gee, my nanny.
I said, where are we going to get the money?
He told me, you get it.
And because you had not been on the high school paper.
No.
And you sure didn't plan to be a journalist.
No.
I guess they watched me work and they figured we needed somebody who could work.
When did, about what time of the year did y'all turn in all of the copy?
Every day.
Right, and when did you turn in the last?
Oh,
A few weeks before.
And it was ready for distribution when?
By the time you graduated?
It was ready for distribution, I think, two or three weeks before graduation.
Everybody got a copy.
You see, that was another thing that bothered me, is that we raised all that money to put out the yearbook, and there were no charge for it.
We gave it to them.
And I think today you pay for it, don't you?
Oh, yes, yes.
Every student pays a fee.
Yeah.
The biggest yearbook in the United States in size and in number of copies today is the Aggieland.
Well, it should be.
Well, I agree.
But see, many other campuses now, the yearbook is going away.
Yeah.
Do you remember where they set up to make the photographs of the individual students?
We had a place there.
I don't remember.
I think it was one of the halls.
And in the first Longhorns, seniors wore tuxedos.
Y'all wore your uniforms, didn't you?
Yes, everybody wore uniforms.
See, you've got to remember that everybody, every student except the casuals, were in uniform.
Did you, by chance, meet Buck Shewitz back in those years?
Oh, yeah.
Please describe what...
I loved Buck.
He was a great guy.
He was a great person.
See, he had been the art editor of the yearbook in 21.
And that one is, next to yours, that one is the best art of any yearbook here.
When my co-author, Jim Clark, and I wrote Spittletop, and we wore the dust jackets.
So I went to Buck and I told him we want a jacket for this book and he delivered it.
And if you ever get a copy of Spittletop and you look at that dust jacket, that's Shewitz.
Make believe that I didn't know Buck and I knew him well.
Describe Buck Shewitz.
I knew him enough to know that he was a compassionate man and full of artistic ideas.
He loved this work.
Oh yes, oh yes.
And he loved this school.
Oh yes.
His drawings should be made a permanent
part of this university.
Well, there are 24 of them downstairs in the main lobby of the MSC all the time right now.
Yeah, I know they've been there, but they ought to have something.
Oh, yes.
They ought to have a room, something dedicated to him, and they started just having them scattered out like they are.
Where did the original for that dust jacket, do you have that?
When the book came out,
We loaned it to this fellow, T.E.
Brown, I think that was his initials, of the Brown Bookstore.
And he had all these books in the window, and he had books drawing, showing the jackets.
And then when we wanted him to return it, he wouldn't return it.
He said somebody stole it.
He's a liar and so and so.
If I ever saw anybody, he just stole it.
That's not fair.
Back to the yearbook.
I don't know why I didn't do something about it.
I don't know why I didn't sue him or something.
When you finished that yearbook, did you present a copy to President Walton?
Was there a special occasion?
when the yearbook was finished?
I think I probably had it.
I think I delivered it to the first copy.
I'm trying to think of the guy who was the Board of Regents.
I think the first copy I delivered to one of the regents by the name of Law.
I forget his first name.
But he was very nice to me.
And he knew my family circumstances.
And he gave me my first degree.
got out of line, gave it to me, did the same thing for the second one.
Oh, how good, how good.
How easy was it to sell ads to the businesses here in Bryan and College?
It wasn't easy.
Did y'all have a party for the, when you finished it, did y'all celebrate in any way?
Oh, Quack and I,
We decided that what we were going to do, pay ourselves a little salary.
And I think we paid ourselves about $50 a month, which helped a lot.
During the years that you were here, what services did the YMCA provide?
What happened at the YMCA?
Well, they had the confectionery for one thing, and then they had services for the students, and they would give you some help in every way that they possibly could.
But then they had a bowling thing in the basement down below.
Was the swimming pool still there?
Yes, I think it was, yeah.
That would have been the only swimming pool anywhere around, wouldn't it?
Yeah, it was there.
Did you get acquainted with Mr. Cashin?
That's a name that's a familiar name.
Cashin, yes.
Cashin.
He was the first director of the Y.
Well, then I must have known him, the name, when you mentioned his name.
Yes, yes.
And see, Red Cashin, that's his son.
Yes, yes, yes.
Did you go to any religious events here while you were a student?
Did you go to church?
Well, occasionally I would.
Where did you?
I'd go to the Episcopal Church.
At South?
We were raised in the Eastern Orthodox Church.
And that's where my Sunday school teacher told me the earth was 5,000 years old.
So they didn't have any Eastern Orthodox Church in this area.
So Episcopal services and rites are the same as practically of the others.
Were there any Sunday night church meetings?
Not that I remember.
Oh, they had meetings, but I don't know.
Was Religious Emphasis Week held in that era?
In the late 30s, I know they had here on the campus one week in the spring when they would have ministers from all denominations come.
They probably did, but I didn't attend those.
Describe the typical A&M student when you were here.
Where was he from?
What kind of income?
What were his basic attitudes?
The average, he was a well-to-do student.
Country or city?
Both.
Most of the students here were well-off.
And what were?
There were a group of us that knew each other's
poverty.
And we tried to mingle with each other because we had the same problems.
Problems at home, problems raising money and everything else.
And there was this other group that were just wealthy people.
Did those well-to-do boys make fun of you poor boys?
No, I don't think that ever took place.
I've never heard of that.
Did it matter where your ancestors came from here at A&M?
No, no.
What was it that pulled Aggies together?
It was the spirit that we realize exists today, the Aggie spirit.
And in that core, when you're in that core and everybody in the college was in the core,
That was a fraternity of its own.
That's one reason why I fought like hell to keep the fraternities from happening in this university.
